## Slide 17 – IT vs DI&A: who does what? 🤝

**Layout suggestion:** Side-by-side comparison (2 columns).

**Key points:**

| Domain | **IT (PMI Tech / IT CX)** | **DI&A** |
|---|---|---|
| **Transactional systems** | Accountable (CRM, ERP, e-commerce, loyalty…) | – |
| **Embedded reporting on source systems** | Accountable | – |
| **APIs & integrations from source systems** | Accountable | – |
| **Enterprise Data Platform (DPaaS / Snowflake)** | Joint support | Accountable (data products) |
| **Reporting & analytics / BI / Power BI** | – | Accountable |
| **AI / ML on transactional apps** | Joint (IT accountable) | Joint (data arch + engineering + science) |
| **Generative AI / agentic tools (DIVA, KAi, MAIA)** | – | Accountable |

**Speaker notes:**
The simplest mental model: **if it's a transactional system feeding data, it's IT. If it's a data product or analytical layer on top of DPaaS, it's DI&A.** AI sits in the middle and we collaborate. Project intake follows the regional DISD (Digital Investment & Strategy Deployment) process; both IT and DI&A heads are part of it.

**Visual suggestions:**
- 2-column comparison with color coding (blue = IT, green = DI&A, gray = shared)

